# DFL Editor Menu Organization

All DFL custom Unity Editor menu items follow a standard path convention. Every new menu item must use these prefixes.

## Top-Level Menu Bar

### `Deep Forest Labs/` -- framework and game tools

All framework utilities, game-specific wizards, and package tools live under this single top-level menu.

| Prefix | Use for | Example |
|--------|---------|---------|
| `Deep Forest Labs/Tools/...` | Framework editor utilities | `Deep Forest Labs/Tools/Validate Project` |
| `Deep Forest Labs/Tools/AssetDatabase/...` | Asset audit, repair, reserialize | `Deep Forest Labs/Tools/AssetDatabase/Reserialize/All Assets` |
| `Deep Forest Labs/Tools/Composite Image/...` | Composite image conversion tools | `Deep Forest Labs/Tools/Composite Image/Settings` |
| `Deep Forest Labs/Tools/SpriteAtlasV2/...` | Sprite atlas utilities | `Deep Forest Labs/Tools/SpriteAtlasV2/Set 'Include In Build' Flag` |
| `Deep Forest Labs/Tools/Prefabs/...` | Prefab tools | `Deep Forest Labs/Tools/Prefabs/Strip All Prefab Overrides` |
| `Deep Forest Labs/{ProjectName}/...` | Game-specific wizards and setup | `Deep Forest Labs/Slumber/Build Main Scene` |
| `Deep Forest Labs/Audio/...` | Audio package tools | `Deep Forest Labs/Audio/Setup Instructions` |

### `Build/` -- build system (stays top-level)

Build commands keep their own top-level menu for fast access via hotkeys (F5-F12). Build-related settings also live here.

```csharp
[MenuItem("Build/Run _F5")]
[MenuItem("Build/Client _F7")]
[MenuItem("Build/Build System Settings %#e")]
```

## Right-Click Context Menu (Project Window)

### `Assets/Deep Forest Labs/Create/...` and `Assets/Deep Forest Labs/Edit/...`

Factory create/edit menu items appear in the Project window right-click context menu. These are generated dynamically by `FactoryCreateMenuItems.cs` for every `ContainerFactory`, `ContainerBuilderFactory`, and MVC `Factory<>` subclass.

The path is controlled by the `[FactoryMenuItem]` attribute:

```csharp
// Produces: Assets/Deep Forest Labs/Create/Slumber/TitleScreen
[FactoryMenuItem("TitleScreen", "Slumber")]
public sealed class TitleScreenFactory : Factory<...> { }
```

Without the attribute, the path is derived from the type's namespace. Use `[FactoryMenuItem]` to keep paths clean.

## Prohibited Patterns

Do NOT place DFL menu items under these prefixes:

```csharp
// BAD -- scattered across Unity's Tools menu
[MenuItem("Tools/DFL/...")]
[MenuItem("Tools/AssetDatabase/...")]
[MenuItem("Tools/Composite Image/...")]

// BAD -- inconsistent naming
[MenuItem("Deep Forest Labs/Utility/...")]

// BAD -- orphaned under Edit
[MenuItem("Edit/Build/...")]

// BAD -- duplicates dynamic factory menus
[CreateAssetMenu(menuName = "Slumber/SessionContainerFactory")]  // on ContainerBuilderFactory subclasses
```

## `[CreateAssetMenu]` Rule

Do NOT use `[CreateAssetMenu]` on `ContainerBuilderFactory` or MVC `Factory<>` subclasses -- the dynamic factory menu system handles these automatically. Only use `[CreateAssetMenu]` on standalone data ScriptableObjects (e.g. `LevelDefinition`) that are not factories.

## Adding New Menu Items

1. Determine the category from the table above
2. Use the full `Deep Forest Labs/...` prefix (or `Build/...` for build commands)
3. For game-specific tools, use `Deep Forest Labs/{ProjectName}/...`
4. For new MVC factories, add `[FactoryMenuItem("Name", "ProjectName")]` -- the framework generates the menu
